info.name: Veracode APIs
info.description: HACKATHON 18 The Veracode REST APIs mirror many of the major application security and administrative tasks that you can perform in the [Veracode Platform](https://web.analysiscenter.veracode.com). You can use the APIs to automate many of these tasks. To understand how the APIs work, Veracode recommends that you familiarize yourself with the [Platform workflow](https://help.veracode.com/r/start) for performing application security testing and reviewing test results. The APIs are designed for members of a software development team responsible for performing application security testing. Developers can use these APIs in rapid build-and-test cycles to fully automate security verification for entire software portfolios and to integrate with internal build and bug-tracking systems. Instead of using the Veracode Platform go through the manual process for submitting a scan request and reviewing the results, you can integrate the API calls directly into your IDEs and build pipelines to automate scanning early and often. The APIs follow the OpenAPI specification and send/receive [JSON](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JSON) or [YAML](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YAML). Complete API documentation, which includes the XML APIs and wrappers, is available in the Veracode Help Center. # Authentication Veracode API authentication requires a Veracode account and API ID/key credentials with Hash-based Message Authentication Code (HMAC) signing. You can use your API credentials for both human user accounts and non-human API service accounts. You can also use these credentials for both username/password and SAML login methods. The APIs use HMAC to digitally sign the HTTP header of each request with your API credentials. HMAC signing provides these security benefits: - Credentials are not sent in the clear as plain text. The API key is never transmitted, but encrypts the HMAC from the sender-side and decrypts it from the server-side. - The HMAC signature validates that the message was not tampered with or altered in transit. Any change to the message invalidates the HMAC. - The HMAC signature includes a nonce (one-time code) that prevents replay attacks. - You can revoke and regenerate the Veracode API credentials to respond to an accidental credentials leak. ## Configure Your Authentication 1. Use the Veracode Platform to create or update a [Veracode account](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/13366636/TzJpiKeK#f3d7bd6a-975f-417d-8ea7-1d6a8bd272c0) with the required roles for each API you want to use. 2. Select an API folder to the left to view the required roles for using that API. If you already have an account with the Administrator role or Admin API role, you can create and manage accounts with the [Identity API](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/13366636/TzJpiKeK#f3d7bd6a-975f-417d-8ea7-1d6a8bd272c0). 3. Use the Identity API or the Veracode Platform to generate or update your API credentials. Optionally, you can store your API credentials securely in an [API credentials file](https://help.veracode.com/r/c_configure_api_cred_file). 4. [Configure HMAC signing](https://help.veracode.com/r/c_enabling_hmac). ## Add Your API Credentials to Postman You can click [**Run in Postman**](https://learning.postman.com/docs/publishing-your-api/run-in-postman/introduction-run-button/), in the top-right corner, to import this collection into the Postman client. You can add your [API credentials](https://help.veracode.com/r/c_api_credentials3) to the collection as variables, so that you can avoid having to enter your credentials for each request. This collection also has pre-configured HMAC signing and includes a variable with the base URL for accessing Veracode - you can start sending requests in Postman immediately after adding your API credentials. To add your API credentials to Postman: 1. In Postman, select the **Veracode APIs** collection. 1. Select the **Variables** tab. 1. In the CURRENT VALUES column, add your API ID to the `id` field and your API key to the `key` field. 1. Click **Save**. You can now send requests in Postman using the APIs in the collection. Ensure you have the required [roles](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/13366636/TzJpiKeK#f3d7bd6a-975f-417d-8ea7-1d6a8bd272c0) for using each API. ![Variables tab in Postman](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/veracode/veracode-rest-apis/main/images/postman-variables-tab.png?token=ATPK4C65STNNCOO322FU5LTAS7XVI) # Getting Started 1. Configure your [authentication](##configure-your-authentication) to obtain your API credentials. **NOTE:** If you already have API credentials, click **Run in Postman**, in the top-right corner, to import this collection into the Postman client. Then, you can [add your API credentials to the collection as variables](Add-Your-API-Credentials-to-Postman) and start sending requests. 2. Send this request to perform a simple test for verifying your authentication using the [Healthcheck API](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/13366636/TzJpiKeK#ceaa491b-9774-4cf0-9bdc-10461914b974): `http --auth-type=veracode_hmac GET https://api.veracode.com/healthcheck/status` A `200` code in the response indicates successful authentication. A `401` code in the response indicates an authentication issue. 3. Visit the [Veracode Help Center](https://help.veracode.com/home) to learn about the tasks and workflows for performing application security testing and reviewing test results. The APIs mirror many of the tasks that you perform in the Veracode Platform. # Status Codes | Code | Status | Description | | --- | --- | --- | | 200 | Successful request | | | 400 | Invalid request | Ensure all components of your request are correct and try again.| | 401 | Access denied | Ensure your [authentication](Authentication) is valid.| | 404 | Not found | Specify a different object or create a new object.| | 500 | Server-side error | Try again or contact Veracode Technical Support. | # Support For help with accessing and using the Veracode APIs, feel free to visit and contribute to the [Veracode Community](https://community.veracode.com). You can also reach out to support@veracode.com. # Terms of Use For information on the terms of use and privacy for our APIs, refer to our legal documentation at https://www.veracode.com/legal-privacy # API Reference

item.description: You can use the Annotations API to annotate findings, including adding comments and proposing, accepting, and rejecting mitigations. CHECK OUT THIS REQUEST!!!!! # Account Requirements Before you can use all endpoints of this API, you must configure your authentication and have one of these Veracode accounts with the required roles: - An API service account with the Results API role - A user account with the Reviewer, Security Lead, or Mitigation Approver role

item.description: You can use the Applications API to manage Veracode applications and development sandboxes. You can use this API to: - Create, update, and delete application profiles and sandboxes - Get detailed information about applications and sandboxes You can use this API with other APIs, such as the [Findings API](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/13366636/TzJpiKeK#3e3b8de9-2dd6-4dc7-9553-eda45efb3345), to simplify common reporting and dashboarding scenarios, enabling you to get the latest data for each application with a single call. You can also access historical state-change information on findings. # Account Requirements Before you can use all endpoints of this API, you must configure your authentication and have one of these Veracode accounts with the required roles: - An API service account with the Upload and Scan API role - A user account with the Creator, Submitter, or Security Lead role

item.description: You can use the Findings API to access information about open and mitigated findings associated with applications and development sandboxes. This API supports Static Analysis, Dynamic Analysis, Manual Penetration Testing, and Software Composition Analysis (SCA) scans. The Findings API simplifies common reporting scenarios, such as obtaining the latest data for each application and accessing historical state-change information on findings. # Account Requirements Before you can use all endpoints of this API, you must configure your authentication and have one of these Veracode accounts with the required roles: - An API service account with the Results API role - A user account with the Reviewer or Security Lead role

request.description: The scan upload endpoint is the first step in scanning JavaScript with Veracode Greenlight, where you upload a ZIP file containing the files you want to scan. Veracode Greenlight supports the scanning of JavaScript embedded in the following file types: ASP, CSS, EHTML, ES, ES6, HANDLEBARS, HBS, HJS, HTM, HTML, JS, JSON, JSP, JSX, MAP, MUSTACHE, PHP, TS, TSX, and XHTML. Greenlight stores the optional header parameters for reporting purposes.

item.description:
You can use the Healthcheck API to perform a simple test for verifying authenticated connectivity to Veracode.

This API provides this lightweight endpoint: ```/healthcheck/status```

You use the endpoint to verify that Veracode services are available and responding to authentication events, instead of using other API calls that can potentially return large volumes of data.

item.description:
You can use the Identity API to manage the administrative tasks for your organization. The API provides endpoints for creating and managing API credentials, Veracode accounts, teams, and business units. # Account Requirements Before you can use all endpoints of this API, you must configure your authentication and have one of these [Veracode accounts](#about-veracode-accounts) with the required roles: - An API service account with the Admin API role. - A user account with the Administrator role. These endpoints of this API do not have any account or role restrictions: - ``/user/self`` - ``/user/api_credentials1`` # About Veracode Accounts Veracode provides two account types: a user account, for real human users, and an API service account, for non-human users. - A user account can access the Veracode Platform and the Veracode APIs. Account permissions are based on the user roles or API roles assigned to the account. - An API service account is for non-human users, such as systems or services, that need to access the Veracode APIs. Veracode recommends that you use this account for automations. For example, you could use this account with the APIs to automate an application analysis that runs unattended and without disruption if a user account expires or becomes disabled. Account permissions are based on the API roles assigned to the account. You can create and manage both account types in the Veracode Platform and with the Veracode Identity APIs. # API Service Account Roles
Role Short Name Role Name Additional Roles Required
submitterapi Upload API - Submit Only Users must have the additional role that matches the type of scan they want to submit: - apisubmitstaticscan - apisubmitdynamicscan - apisubmitmanualscan - noteamrestrictionapi - apisubmitanyscan
uploadapi Upload and Scan API Users must have the additional role that matches the type of scan they want to run: - apisubmitstaticscan - apisubmitdynamicscan - apisubmitmanualscan - noteamrestrictionapi - apisubmitanyscan

item.description: You can use the Veracode SCA Agent REST API to programmatically extract high-level workspace information on specific Veracode Agent-Based Scan workspaces or all workspaces to which you have access. You can also filter your workspaces on library, vulnerability, and license. **Note:** To prevent your API requests being blocked, provide your company, application name, or email domain in your User-Agent header so that Veracode Technical Support can address any issues. The Veracode SCA Agent REST API requires an Enterprise subscription plan. To get a quote for an upgrade to Enterprise, send an email to contact@veracode.com. **Note:** There are two host URLs for the Veracode SCA Agent API. If you use SourceClear API credentials, the host URL is api.sourceclear.io. If you use Veracode API credentials, the host URL is api.veracode.com/srcclr. # Account Requirements Before you can use all endpoints of this API, you must configure your authentication and have one of these Veracode accounts with the required roles: - An API service account with the Upload and Scan API role - A user account with the Creator, Submitter, or Security Lead role The SCA Agent API supports both Veracode API credentials and [SourceClear API credentials](Generate-SourceClear-API-Credentials). **Note:** When you configure your HMAC authentication, follow the instructions as written, except use the SourceClear credentials instead of the Veracode API credentials. ## Generate SourceClear API Credentials The Veracode SCA Agent API requires that you use SourceClear API credentials Veracode API credentials for authentication. To generate SourceClear API credentials: 1. From the Veracode Platform, select **Scans & Analysis** > **SourceClear Software Composition Analysis**. 2. From the username menu in the top-right corner, select **Personal Settings** > **API Credentials**. 3. Click **Generate**. 4. Configure your [HMAC authentication](https://help.veracode.com/r/orRWez4I0tnZNaA_i0zn9g/XXYI5I0hv4r7EWbHKAxW1Q "Some Veracode products require that you provide your Veracode API credentials using a Veracode API credentials file."). **Note:** When you configure your HMAC authentication, follow the instructions as written, except use the SourceClear credentials instead of the Veracode API credentials.

item.description: You can use the Dynamic Analysis API to automate major dynamic scanning tasks. This API enables you to programmatically initiate dynamic scanning with the flexibility necessary for incorporating this type of security scanning into your Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC). The API endpoints perform these tasks: - Create analyses with URL scans - Configure analyses and URL scans - Schedule and run analyses - Link analyses to Veracode application profiles - After completing a dynamic analysis scan, you can use the [Findings API](https://documenter.getpostman.com/view/13366636/TzJpiKeK#3e3b8de9-2dd6-4dc7-9553-eda45efb3345) to get information on a discovered flaw. # Account Requirements Before you can use all endpoints of this API, you must configure your authentication and have one of these Veracode accounts with the required roles: - An API service account with the Upload and Scan API role. - A User account with the Security Lead, Creator, or Submitter role.
